Where can we find evidence of prominence? Prominence of a word is determined
 by three parameters that are expressed in sound: A local maxima or minima
 of the fundamental frequency contour, longer duration and a high energy
 regions of speech 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rosenberg2006correlation"

\end_inset

.
 More interestingly, in this work we hypothesis that linguistic features
 contribute to prominence.
 For example, since content words tend to introduce new information, they
 are likely to be accented more often than function words.
 Another example that influences accent is the presence of phrases which
 is a sequence of accented words within a sentence.
 Within the phrase there will be another dimension of accentuation in the
 form of a word or a syllable.
 Another noticeable trend is that the local surrounding of a prominent word
 can not be prominent.
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kimballavoidance"

\end_inset

 who claims that we are not capable of perciving clashes resulted by adjacent
 prominent words and adjust our hearing to perceive a modified sentence
 that detaches and avoids adjacency.
 This conclusion might also suggest that sentence production involves scattering
 prominece to non-prominent (lapse) environments by avoiding accenting two
 or more units in a row.
\end_layout

